    "summary": "**Topics:** Mobile game user acquisition (ad buying), post-IDFA advertising economics, \"brainwashing\" ad creatives, SLG sub-gameplay marketing, internet entertainment simplification trends.\n**Entities:** Apple (IDFA policy), SLG mobile games, DianDian Data (research source), Z Generation users, short-form video/live commerce platforms.\n**Dates:** 2018 (onset of industry pessimism toward ad buying), 2021 (Apple's default IDFA opt-out implementation), 2026 (publication/copyright year).\n**Definitions/Concepts:** \"Post-IDFA era\" (privacy-restricted ad targeting environment), \"brainwashing creatives\" (simplified, repetitive, emotion-driven ad formats), \"sub-gameplay acquisition\" (marketing using secondary/minigame mechanics to attract users), \"CAC > LTV death spiral\" (unsustainable user acquisition economics).\n**Procedures/Strategies:** Optimizing ad creatives via core mechanic symbolization, emotion-driven repetition, and AI-generated variant scaling; balancing gameplay tone with conversion metrics; leveraging sub-gameplay ads to bypass targeting limitations.\n**Claims:** Ad buying remains the dominant acquisition channel despite rising costs and stock competition; brainwashing creatives outperform in data validation despite polarized reception; sub-gameplay ads rescued SLG games from unsustainable CAC/LTV ratios; internet entertainment is shifting toward extreme simplification, directly influencing game marketing strategies.\n**Tables/Figures:** Contains a DianDian Data research figure/chart illustrating mobile game ad trends, SLG market shifts, or a structured breakdown of brainwashing ad advantages/disadvantages.\n**Metrics:** User Acquisition Cost (CAC), Long-term Lifetime Value (LTV), ad cost escalation, conversion rates, algorithmic traffic allocation efficiency.\n**Evid..."
