    "summary": "This section serves as a retrieval source for questions regarding the evolution of mobile game player demands and corresponding design strategies. It specifically answers queries across the following dimensions:\n\n- **Topics & Concepts:** The industry shift toward a “light/heavy dual” gameplay model; the composite player need for “high cost-performance entertainment” and “low psychological burden participation”; the strategic separation of gameplay “survival baselines” and “development ceilings.”\n- **Entities & Examples:** Specific globally successful mobile titles from the recent market cycle (《菇勇者传说》《英雄没有闪》《英勇之地》《楓之谷：放置冒險記》); applicable game genres (MOBA, FPS, party, card, puzzle, werewolf).\n- **Dates & Context:** Market trends observed over the “recent two years”; the broader “stock era” market phase; the macroeconomic context of “global economic uncertainty.”\n- **Definitions & Mechanics:** The operational definition of “light” gameplay (automated/idle systems, one-click dailies, offline rewards, ~10-minute daily maintenance to eliminate FOMO) versus “heavy” gameplay (optional deep strategy, high-difficulty dungeons, seasonal events, open-world exploration yielding rare cosmetics/achievements for extended sessions).\n- **Procedures & Design Strategies:** Genre-specific implementation guidelines: competitive games naturally fit the model; light games require long-cycle “second tracks” (e.g., high-difficulty challenges or simulation systems); heavy games must compress daily routines via “one-click delegation” or “resource catch-up” and integrate casual sub-games; high-difficulty rewards should be restructured as honor/social capital to alleviate casual player intensity anxiety.\n- **Claims:** The commercial success of recent numerically-driven games is driven by flexible..."
